post_text:
The California Living Museum (CALM) announced today that the 18th annual HolidayLights will take place as a drive-through experience in light of the COVID-19 pandemic and the anticipation that large gatherings will continue to be prohibited for some time. The event will return on Saturday, Nov. 28 and run nightly through Jan. 2, except on Christmas, from 5:30 p.m. to 9 p.m. (the last vehicle will be admitted at 8:30 p.m.).

Passenger vehicles (no RVs, busses or limousines will be allowed) will embark on a mile-long winding path through CALM’s expansive parking lot, flanked by everyone’s favorite dazzling animated light displays.

Information on how to purchase tickets, prices and other details will be forthcoming over the next several weeks.

post_text:
Doing our part to help get the word out...
The California Independent System Operator (CalISO) has notified the utility companies (PG&E and SCE locally) that there's a power shortage throughout California and we'll continue to see rolling blackouts for the next few days. Power supply estimates are harder now with everyone at home so WE NEED YOUR HELP to keep Kern County powered up.

From 3 to 10 PM try to cut your power usage as much as possible. During this this time frame:

⏲Set your thermostat to 78 or higher
🔌Avoid using large appliances
❄️After 10 PM, cool your home to 72

And of course, turn off lights and electronics when you're not using them.💡 Our biggest concern is keeping the power on for our elderly neighbors and those who are dependent on medical devices.

post_text: The McKinney-Vento Homeless Assistance Act ensures educational rights and protections for children and youth experiencing homelessness. Any family that is in an inadequate living situation due to loss of housing, economic hardship or similar reasons, and are interested in additional support and resources for your children in school, should complete an online referral form (http://bit.ly/ReferKernMV) or contact our education liaison, Rolando Hernandez, at 661-636-4900 or rhernandez@kern.org.

post_text: Attention Parents: If you’re looking for childcare as we transition to the new school year, MyChildCare.ca.gov provides information on all licensed center-based and family childcare homes in Kern County. For more information about local daycare options and questions about childcare subsidies, please call Community Connection for Childcare, at 661-861-5200, M-F, 7:30 am to 5 pm, or visit kernchildcare.org.

After months of intensive research and success at district and county-level competitions, champions were recognized at the 2020 California History Day Virtual State Contest. Sixty-two students will represent California at the National History Day Virtual competition, June 14-18, 2020, four of whom are Kern County Students.

Matthew Fan and Thomas Wilson from Fruitvale Junior High placed first in the Junior Group Documentary category with their project titled “Leo B. Hart and the Children of the Dustbowl: Breaking Educational and Social Barriers.

Evan Noel and Madeline Mykytiuk from Endeavour Elementary School placed first in the Elementary Group Poster category with their project titled “With No Hope in Sight: Operation Seasweep - Breaking Barriers for Vietnam's Boat People.”

For complete results, go to: https://kern.org/wp-content/blogs.dir/4/files/sites/4/2020/05/KernWinnersReport.pdf

KCSOS issued the following statement today in response to Governor Gavin Newsom’s remarks that public schools might start the next school year as early as late July or early August:

Kern County school districts already begin in late-July to mid-August, earlier than many districts throughout the state that start after Labor Day. All Kern County school communities share the Governor’s goals of re-opening our schools as quickly as possible to serve our students. The decision to alter the academic calendar would ultimately be made by local school boards after careful consideration and input from parents, staff, local health experts and other local community stakeholders.

post_text: It is with a very heavy heart that we inform you of the passing of Olga “Tati’ Gullane, a longtime member of the KCSOS family. We are saddened by Olga’s unexpected death after battling health issues, which caused her to retire last fall. Olga began her career with KCSOS in September, 1987, and served as an Early Start Instructional Assistant. Olga left a lasting impression on every one of her students and their families. She had a knack for getting into the good graces of even the most reluctant toddler and never left a home visit without teasing at least one smile from a nervous parent. We extend our thoughts, prayers and condolences to her family, friends and colleagues.

post_text: This year’s California Academic Decathlon competition took place virtually this past Friday. Kern County had two qualifying teams — Stockdale and Frontier. Stockdale took 14th place in the Division I competition and Frontier placed 6th among Division II teams. As in the traditional in-person format, the virtual competition featured objective tests in which decathletes had 30 minutes to complete tests in Art, Economics, Language and Literature, Mathematics, Music, Science, and Social Science. Way to go students and coaches!

post_text: Educating our community's young people is just one of the many, many services that public schools provide. Schools are an essential safety net for so many in our community, providing a safe and welcoming space for our children, supervision and social emotional supports every day. With 73% of countywide students eligible for free and reduced meals and some 30% living in poverty, nutrition services are hugely important. The folks out on the front lines ensuring that our kids stay well fed while our schools are closed are truly heroes! Please WATCH and SHARE this uplifting video and thank them for their dedication.

post_text: Congratulations to KCSOS school nurse Beth Berchtold who was recently honored with the Excellence in School Nursing Award from the central valley section of the California School Nurses Organization (CSNO). post_text: The third bi-annual conference for parents of children with special needs, presented by the Kern County Consortium SELPA, will take place on Friday, Jan. 24 from 8:30 am to 3 pm at Hodel’s in Bakersfield. The conference is intended to empower parents who are struggling to meet the needs of their complex families. The conference will host well-respected speaker Karlyn Farber, a Board Certified Behavior Analyst (BCBA) and professional educator with 30-plus years of experience and Clinical Supervisor for California Spectrum Services. The cost is only $10 and includes continental breakfast and lunch. To register for Specially Yours, visit http://kern.org/selpa. The registration deadline is Friday, Jan. 17. For more information, contact SELPA coordinator Lee Knotts-Martin at 636-4884.

Here's your chance to help increase literacy in our community. The Kern County Community Reading Project trains community members to become reading coaches for at-risk second graders. Volunteers visit a classroom one day per week for an hour. Those interested in volunteering during the spring semester 2020 can choose from two upcoming training sessions: Wednesday, January 8, 2020 from 3 p.m. to 5 p.m. and Thursday, January 16, 2020 from 5:30 p.m. to 7:30 p.m. Trainings are held at 1300 17th Street, Room 1B. No pre-registration is necessary.

post_text: Congratulations to the eight Kern County elementary schools that were selected by the California Department of education as 2020 California Distinguished Schools. Schools are awarded for closing the achievement gap, achieving exceptional student performance, and ensuring highly successful school climate efforts ranging from real-time conflict resolution to positive behavior intervention. The following Kern County Schools were among 323 selected statewide: Cesar E. Chavez Elementary School (Bakersfield City School District); Morningside Elementary School (Delano Union Elementary School District); Endeavour Elementary School (Fruitvale Elementary School District); Fairview and W A Kendrick elementary schools (Greenfield Union School District); Midway School (Midway School District); Buena Vista and Stockdale elementary schools (Panama-Buena Vista Union School District).

Get your HolidayLights tickets early and beat the crowds! Tickets for the California Living Museum’s 17th Annual HolidayLights go on sale starting TODAY (Nov. 22) at all Kern Schools Federal Credit Union branches. You do not have to be a member to purchase these advance tickets!

Ticket prices remain the same as in past years: Adults - $12; Seniors 60+ and Youth 13 to 17 - $10; Kids 3 to 12 - $6; Kids under 3 – FREE. CALM members and military receive 50% off. In addition, you can receive $2 off all ticket prices for tickets good Monday- Thursday the first two weeks of December.

HolidayLights starts Saturday, November 30, 2019 and runs through Saturday, January 4, 2020, and is open every night except Christmas from 5:30 PM to 9:00 PM (gates close at 8:30 PM).

Come enjoy HolidayLights at CALM – Voted as Bakersfield’s Best Annual Event, named by the Los Angeles Times as one of the top ten light shows in the Western US, and nominated recently by USA Today as one of the top twenty light shows in the nation!

Each was also awarded the Daryl Thiesen Attendance Improvement Award. Thiesen, who passed away in February from complications with ALS, was a longtime employee of the Kern County Superintendent of Schools office who worked tirelessly for at-risk students in our community. Way to go girls...Daryl would certainly be proud!

post_text:
It is with much sadness that we inform you of the passing of Lynn Taylor, an employee with KCSOS's division of Special Education. We are saddened by Lynn’s passing and extend our prayers and condolences to her family.

Lynn began her career with our office on March 1, 1988 and spent the last 30 years providing exceptional service to the students and families that were lucky enough to be served by her. Starting first as an Instructional Aide, and then later becoming an Early Start Learning Assistant, she was a wonderful friend, and dedicated, passionate employee always willing to go the extra mile for her students and their families. That dedication extended outside of work hours to causes near to her heart, including serving as a Board Member and Chair for the Camp KEEP Foundation. Her dry sense of humor, knowledge, and pride for her students will be sorely missed.

post_text: Congratulations to Dr. Lisa Gilbert on her appointment as Deputy Superintendent of KCSOS. Dr. Gilbert will continue to oversee the Instructional Services Division, while taking on additional responsibilities primarily focused on KCSOS’s expanded local and statewide initiatives. Dr. Gilbert has dedicated her career to education having served as a teacher, counselor, administrator and Superintendent of the Tehachapi Unified School District prior to joining KCSOS in 2014. For the past four years, she has led KCSOS’s efforts to develop a model of support to provide differentiated assistance and other support to local districts.

post_text: Migrant Education students from the Kern High, Wasco Union High and Taft Union High School districts have been attending Saturday workshops all year on how our the local, state, and federal government works and how it impacts Kern County. The culminating activity is a one week program with the Close Up Foundation in Washington D.C. where students participate in mock elections and the mock legislative process (how bills are passed). Students visit all the monuments and learn the history behind each one. In addition, meetings with our congressional representatives are set up in the nation's capital where they get to asks our representatives questions regarding issues that affect Kern County. Real world learning at its finest!

post_text: We are very saddened to have to inform you of the passing of a KCSOS employee. Dawn Johnson, Retirement Technician I, passed away Sunday after a sudden illness. Dawn began her career at KCSOS in 1985 as a Data Entry Operator and has held many positions through the years including: Media Clerk, Food Service Worker, Bindery Clerk, Account Clerk, Payroll Technician, and Retirement Technician. Dawn had an infectious smile and vivacious personality and will be greatly missed by her co-workers and the districts she served. Dawn is survived by her husband Bruce, her sons Michael and Kevin, and five grandchildren. Please keep Dawn’s family in your thoughts and prayers during this difficult time. Services are pending.

post_text: KCSOS will host a Youth Mental Health First Aid workshop on May 14, from 7:30 am - 4:30 pm. The $25 workshop is designed for individuals serving youth in the community, law enforcement, social services, health care, education, parents, and other areas. The course teaches participants how to help someone who is developing a mental health problem or experiencing a mental health crisis. Youth Mental Health First Aid covers risk factors and warning signs of mental health concerns as well as a 5-step action plan to help an adolescent in need of mental health support. REGISTER HERE: https://kern.k12oms.org/eventdetail.php?id=166440

post_text: And the results are in!! Thanks to everyone who voted for CALM in The Bakersfield Californian’s Annual Readers’ Poll. CALM was voted "Best Of" in THREE categories: Best Family/Kid Entertainment, Best Annual Event-HolidayLights at CALM and Best Museum. Accepting the honor(s) on behalf of CALM staff, volunteers, Kern County Superintendent of Schools and the CALM Foundation are (l-r) Sharon Adams, Curator of Animals and Lana Fain, Zoo Manager. Check out all the results in Bakersfield Life magazine inside Tomorrow's Bakersfield Californian.

KCSOS has announced the names of the six Kern County Classified School Employees of the Year...

Carmen West, Cook – Norris School District; Kirk Kindred, Lead Maintenance Worker – Taft Union High School; Christine Swall, Special Education Classroom Aide – Muroc Unified School District; Jose Silva, Warehouse Specialist/Bus Driver – Norris School District; Virginia Rose, Extended Day Assistant Sr. – Norris School District; Cindy White, Administrative Assistant – Norris School District.

These employees will move on to represent Kern in the State Classified School Employees of the Year competition. State winners will be announced in late April and will be recognized at a special event in Sacramento in May. Way to go!!

post_text: The Bakersfield Police Department hosted its 4th annual Audible Easter Egg hunt today for KCSOS students who are blind or visually impaired. Plastic eggs with audible beepers were "hidden" in an expansive grass field and students used their hearing and the help of BPD officers to find the eggs. Thanks to the Bakersfield Police Department, Target and Frito Lay for helping make this event a success!

post_text: In celebration of the Week of the Young Child, KCSOS in partnership with First 5 Kern, officially launched the Kern Early Stars program during a special event held today at the Oaks Children’s Center in Southwest Bakersfield. Kern Early Stars assesses and awards stars to child development centers and providers that voluntarily participate, with a focus on ensuring a commitment to quality improvement. For more info., visit www.kernearlystars.org.

post_text:
Hundreds of 4th through 12th grade students took part in Kern County's 31st annual Regional Science Fair today at the Rabobank Convention Center. The annual event is the culmination of months of hard work for students who rose through their school and district ranks for a chance to showcase their science projects and compete at the county level. Stay tuned for this year's results!

First or second place finishers may be eligible to compete in the 68th annual California Science Fair to be held at the California Science Center in Los Angeles on April 29-30.

post_text: Congrats to Delano High School and Cesar E. Chavez High School (also in Delano), along with Rosedale Middle School, for being named to this year's list of California Distinguished Schools by the California Department of Education. The three Kern County schools were among 162 middle and high schools statewide to receive the honor — each a shining example of not just excellent teaching, learning, and collaboration, but highly successful school climate efforts. Way to go!

Online registration for the 19th annual Kern County Teacher Recruitment Fair is now open at the link below. Registration closes Friday, Feb. 15.

The event will take place Saturday, February 23, 2019 from 8:00 a.m. to noon at the Larry E. Reider Education Center, 2000 K Street in Bakersfield. Individuals who are fully credentialed, intern-eligible, career technical education teachers, and holders of bachelor’s degrees or higher are invited to attend.
